<DOC><DOCNO> AP881230-0022 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-12-30-88 0416EST</FILEID><FIRST>r a PM-Bakkers-Television     12-30 0260</FIRST><SECOND>PM-Bakkers-Television,0268</SECOND><HEAD>Jim And Tammy Bakker Plan Return To Television</HEAD><DATELINE>CHARLOTTE, N.C. (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Jim Bakker and his wife, Tammy, willreturn to television for the first time in nearly two years Mondaywith a live show broadcast from their living room, a newspaperreported today.   Six independent television stations across the nation will carrythe program, said The Charlotte Observer, quoting unidentifiedsources.   Bakker, who was indicted with three associates this month oncharges of misusing millions of dollars in PTL money, could not bereached for comment Thursday.   Bakker has not had a regular TV show since resigning from PTL inMarch 1987 after widely publicized allegations of his 1980 sexualencounter with church secretary Jessica Hahn and payments to keepher quiet. He and Tammy Bakker were co-hosts of PTL's ``Jim andTammy Show.''   The Bakkers' new show will be broadcast live from their livingroom near Pineville Monday through Friday and will be carried onstations in Albany, N.Y.; Atlanta; Chico, Calif.; Los Angeles;Philadelphia; and San Diego, the Observer said.   Bakker attorney Jim Toms of Hendersonville said in a telephoneinterview Thursday night that the Bakkers had been preparing toreturn to television, but could not confirm when the return wouldtake place.   While at PTL, the Bakkers' show was broadcast by about 180television stations.   Asked what kind of program the Bakkers are planning, a sourcereplied, ``The same as before.''   ``It's real important,'' the source said of Monday's show. ``It'sthe first day back. It's not going to be any fly-by-night thing.''</TEXT></DOC>